title: Robotic arm polar printer

description.text: A robotic arm printer to be used with geared hobby motors

These parts can either be made with a reprap or a cnc milling machine. The motors are from robokitsworld.com
http://robokitsworld.com/index.php?main_page=product_info&cPath=2_3&products_id=255
There is a forum about robotic arms including this design on the reprap forum.

comments.text: HI.
comments.author: Auzze

comments.text: there is really no point to making this, unless you want to have a robotic arm for other reasons. It will not work as a reprap. I am working on a new design that works much better, using threaded rod. Here is the wiki for that:
comments.author: Auzze

comments.text: Unfortunately the gears on this design are a huge pain, and not very accurate, so I do not recommend building it. I have designed a new robotic arm that is driven by only threaded rod. This will eliminate the error associated with making your own gears. Another good thing is that it will only need a foot of 1/4" threaded rod, so the cost will be very small. Believe me, it is a huge improvement.

Minirobot construido todas las piezas, dándole un estilo diferente con una apariencia de Nave Interestelar, posee los soportes para la colocación de dos servos estandares, dos baterías de 9V que forman una estabilidad en el centro de masa del minirobot compensando el peso de los servos y los sensores ultrasónicos.
Las conexiones son por acople, el diseño superior como el inferior se unen para formar una sola estructura para darle mayor rigidez.
Todas las partes del minirobot se le ha dado un soporte para evitar cualquier quiebre en la estructura, haciendo un diseño sólido y ligero.
Se ha creado un acople especial que se desliza por una rendija del soporte de la rueda loca y esta se desliza a la vez por una rendija para la estructura principal, permitiendo graduar la altura de la rueda loca y a su vez darle mayor rigidez.
La rueda se inserta a presión para ello se ha creado unos cortes que permitan ingresar la esfera y esta gire y no se salga.

El diseño surge como parte del proyecto del seminario de impresoras 3D en la Universidad Carlos III de Madrid, el diseño es de originalidad propia. En el archivo Nicolas_minirobot.scad se podrá encontrar todas las piezas diseñadas, con la facilidad de poder comentar cada pieza y generar el stl. Además de poder ver la estructura junto con los servos, arduino y baterías solo descomentado el código inicial que llama los stl. Los accesorios que se usaron de referencia son los siguientes:
us_sensor_hc-sr04.stl
servo_futabaS3003.stl
Batteries.stl
arduino_solid_holes.stl Además se ha subido los stl de cada una de las piezas, las cuales son:
Nk_sujetador_rueda_loca.stl
Nk_sujetador_bateria.stl
Nk_soporte_ultrasonico.stl
Nk_soporte_rueda_loca.stl
Nk_montaje_superior.stl
Nk_montaje_inferior.stl
Nk_esfera.stl

description.text:
Organizer for small office objects.

It consists of 8 pieces:

  • Pencil Pot.
  • Drawer cabinet.
  • Drawers (4).
  • Tray.
  • Pocket.

Once printed, glue the pencil pot, drawer cabinet, tray and pocket. For ABS, PVC cement is suitable.

Because the walls are thin (2 mm) the pencil pot and the drawer cabinet may have delamination problems if printed with ABS. To try to solve it, raise the temperature of the extruder to 260° C, lower the printing speed to 40 mm/s and if possible use an enclosed printer to avoid rapid cooling and drafts. I have put a 42W halogen lamp pointing at the piece, to keep it warm between 70 and 90 º C. (See pictures 1 and 2).

Organizador para pequeños objetos de oficina.

Se compone de 8 piezas:

  • Lapicero.
  • Cajonera.
  • Cajones (4).
  • Bandeja.
  • Bolsillo lateral.

Debido a que la paredes son finas (2 mm) el lapicero y la cajonera pueden presentar problemas de deslaminación si se imprime con ABS. to build it take the 2 upper rings and the lower ring and place the 24 ribs alternately around.

The tolerances are a bit relaxed. This could be due to the overhang printing without support. Example: I printed two just pieces (sequentially). One of them fit perfectly, the other did not catch the pipettor barrel as it should have.

The part should probably be printed slowly (30-40mm/s) and at 0.1mm or better resolution.

NOTE: the design should be printed with the threaded section on top for best results.

description.text:
This is Jyn's Erso Baton Tonfa completely remodeled using Autodesk Fusion 360. The original version is designed to be printed vertically, whereas my version designed to be printed horizontally.
I'm using an aluminium tube 25mm in diameter as inner tube, so the assembled baton is pretty solid. The "cap.stl" and "tube inner.stl" should be glued to it on opposite sides. I'm cutting the tube little shorter than a space inside "cap" than i lock it with glued "tube inner.stl" inside main part, apply some glue to the free side and put "cap" over, so the cap fits tight to the main part. The main part inner side need some sanding, so the inner tube shoul move inside pretty tight.
Also you'll need an M4 nut and M4 screw for the handle.

If you don't want to print it by yourself, you can order one here: https://www.etsy.com/listing/503669105/jyn-erso-baton-tonfa-rogue-one-weapon

A completely printable bowstring-style equatorial sundial, adjustable for either hemisphere and a large range of latitude.

Print the equatorial band, the bow, the base and the north and south caps. Use a 3 mm rod (filament or a kebab stick works well) for the gnomon, install end caps, attach equatorial band with the middle hour mark (noon mark) aligned with the centre of the bow. Make sure to install the band into the bow to match the direction of shadow advancement with time. Insert bow into base, use the scale on the bow and the mark on the base top to set the inclination of the gnomon for your latitude. Use a compass and the local magnetic declination to point your sundial north/south. Enjoy! The conical caps are hard to print perfectly on most printers, if you prefer you can omit them and use the alternative bow (with no extensions to support them). If you use smaller filament, or wish to use a fine wire for the gnomon you can adjust the geometry in the OpenSCAD file and regenerate. Similarly if you are very close to the poles or equator you may wish to alter the gap in the band based on the earliest sunrise and latest sunset for your location. You can compensate for your longitude relative to your timezone by positioning the band off centre up to one hour mark. This can also be used to compensate for daylight savings time, but as there are no digits on the scale you may prefer to just make the adjustment mentally. Naturally you'll need to compensate for the Equation of Time variation over the year, but the calibration marks are only to the nearest quarter hour and the maximum error is about 20 minutes... There is also no compensation for atmospheric refraction, but the device is too small for very high accuracy anyway. Darker opaque colours are the easiest to read. Darker colours may also be more UV stable if you are going to leave your sundial outdoors. Bugs: The Band/Bow joint should be more robust. PLA may soften and slump in the hot sun. It should really have pretty numbering, not just line markings. I should really compute the min/max sunrise/sunset times for the specified location and set the gap (if any) in the equatorial band automatically. It should include an annalemma plot on the base. Should probably have a cursor for equinox and solstice indication. It kinda looks like a bird - that may be a feature. This is my first sundial, I got obsessed with them last night and I've only been studying them for about 18 hours, I may have stuffed something up. :)

description.text:
A valve core remover tool that sits axially concentric with a presta valve core, & features coarse knurls for grip.

7 Feb 17: By the way, these knurls are inscribed in a hex profile, the outer circle (furthest outside tips of the hexagon) of which measures 9.44 mm in diameter. You may be able to use a small wrench to turn it if you want. I don't imagine you would need that much torque though.

Print it & tell me what happens. It works in my head, but I've never actually used one before. I checked some images of real ones to verify the design, but for some reason it's bothering me that it might not work.

The OD of the presta valve wrench flat area (excluding the wrench flats) is approximately 5.1 mm. The imaginary cylinder including this feature, up to the larger threaded length, is approximately 13.50 mm.

So I made a cutout to clear this imaginary "presta valve wrench flats area", a cylinder of 5.1 * 1.15 = 5.87 mm x 15.50 mm (13.50 + 2 mm for clearance).

The actual nominal wrench flats measure about 4.11 mm across, & a chain tool so happens to have "wrench jaws" spaced about 4.12 mm across which work perfectly to turn the valve core flats.

Accounting for shrinkage & 3D printer dimensional tolerance, I made my "jaws" with a spacing/radius of 4.12/2 * 1.15 = 2.39 mm.

Referenced the Stan's NoTubes Valve Core Remover Tool (http://www.notubes.com/Core-Remover-Tool-P350.aspx) for handle dimensions:

  • 9.44 mm OD for handle (asked via email)
  • 6.93 mm protrusion for valve core remover part
  • 1.53 mm jaw ID-OD difference
  • 1.97 mm jaw depth

See the dimensions STL for the imported & scaled image for reference.

Found out that a chain tool works fine for removing valve cores. http://www.notubes.com/Core-Remover-Tool-P350.aspx Used for general dimensions

6 Feb 17: Might add extra ends like the Park Tool one (http://www.parktool.com/product/valve-core-tool-vc-1), but I'd need one of them first or dimensions from a kind stranger. Probably not going to buy one myself.

7 Feb 17: Added 1 mm fillets to the ends.

27 Feb 17: finally got around to test printing it. It's too big. Until I notify otherwise, I would try scaling it down a few percent or so.

Foldable, storable, collapsable card holder for boardgames and card games. There are other card display things out there but none that can fold down and store away easily. This should have the same volume as a small hardback book when it's collapsed so it should fit in game boxes between plays. It can hold both euro and american style cards. If you notice anything you'd like me to upgrade, let me know!

There are two files. One is a wider "deployed" version that should print fine as-is. Another is a modified "folded" version that should work in smaller volume printers. The folded version is 65mm wide, and the deployed version is approx 90mm wide when standing. Cards are generally 60mm wide.

Notes:

Set support overhang to 65 to 70 degrees.
Recommended you take long-print precautions on your model to prevent warping. For me with PLA that was 55c heated build plate, 55c ambient temp.

Print it sideways with the round stops flat on the build platform. It's designed to use almost no support material except around the hinges as long as your material can support a 56 degree overhang. The round stops are primarily to prevent warping during printing and to ensure adhesion to the platform. If they annoy you on the finished product you can trim them off easily.

No assembly required, but that means you need to have a pretty dialed in print calibration. If your circles aren't circles in each corner of your build platform you will be a sad person trying to make this one.

Even on its side, it's both wide and tall. Make sure to orient it so that your print head, carriage, and tubes do not accidentally hit or snag any of part of the model as it traverses. I lost several of my prototypes to this problem.

Print warping is a problem if you're not careful. The baffles and holes are all there to help alleviate the cooling stresses. So even PLA with it's wicked shrinking tendency should work okay as long as you make sure it stays flat and your chamber stays conducive to long prints.

You can shrink this by up to 5% to fit it in the build volume, but past that your printer better be very very precise with well behaved material gain on x and y axis lest you fuse the hinges. If you print with a raft expect to spend a little time cleaning the bed-ward sides of the hinges to ensure smooth action.

Low-Post Printing Cleanup

If you printed without a raft the only post printing cleaning up should be to use a needle nose pliers to pull support material out of the space between the hinges. I would avoid trying to clear the hinges by spinning them before at least cleaning some of the support material lest you break the card platform. It's pretty strong and can hold lots of cards, but PLA is brittle and doesn't like this type of sudden stress.

I realized there were no foldable, collapsable card holders for board games so I started to make one. I took a standard book hinge and used that as inspiration for the full design. This is Rev 5. Suggestions welcome.
